{"title_page": "Ekkehard W\u00f6lk", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2009}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Ekkehard W\u00f6lk\n| image                 = Ekkehard_W\u00f6lk.JPG\n| caption            = Ekkehard W\u00f6lk in 2007.\n| image_size            = 360px\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_date                = {{birth date|df=yes|1967|6|14}}\n| origin              = [[Schleswig]], Germany\n| instrument          = Piano\n| genre               = [[Jazz]], [[Classic]]\n| occupation          = Pianist<br>Composer<br>Arranger\n}}\n\n'''Ekkehard W\u00f6lk''' is a German pianist, arranger, and composer, working in both classical and jazz idioms.\n\n==Early life==\nHe was born in [[Schleswig]], Federal Republic of Germany in 1967. W\u00f6lk started piano training at the age of seven. His classical music teachers and professors were Kevin McKenna (Dublin, Ireland), Hartmut Leistritz (conservatory of Lubeck), Eliza Hansen (conservatory of Hamburg), and Gunther Daubler (conservatory of Wurzburg). His jazz improvisation teachers were Walter Norris, Dieter Glawischnig, Richie Beirach, Philip Catherine, John Taylor, [[Fred Hersch]], and [[Barry Harris]].\n\nAfter graduating from high school in 1987 he studied historical and systematic musicology at the university of Hamburg and later in the mid-1990s at the Humboldt University in Berlin.\n\nFrom 1988 to 1994 he studied classical piano at the conservatories in Hamburg and Lubeck. 1994 he graduated as a concert pianist and music pedagogue.<ref>Online Encyclopedia of Jazz Musicians</ref>\n\nIn 1995 W\u00f6lk moved to Berlin and continued working as a pianist, composer, arranger, bandleader and accompanist\nmostly in classical and jazz musical genres.\n\n==Silent films==\nA couple of his works for German films have been released on DVD by New York-based company [[Kino International (company)|Kino]]. Secrets of a Soul by [[G. W. Pabst]] from 1926 with Werner Krauss was released in 2008 and The Finances of the Grand Duke by [[F. W. Murnau|Murnau]].\n\nWith the silent movie music trio Blanc Et Noir<ref>{{cite web |url=www.music-for-silent-movies.eu |website=Blanc et Noir |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref> he also performed at the Palais Royal Des Beaux Arts in Brussels, accompanying silent short comedies.\n\nIn the summer of 2019 W\u00f6lk presented his new original quartet composition for the classic German film ''Madame DuBarry'' (Ernst Lubitsch, 1919) during the open-air summer festival of UFA Filmn\u00e4chte in Berlin.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ufa-filmnaechte.de/en/ |website=UFA Filmn\u00e4chte}}</ref>\n\n==Recordings==\nHe has seven albums released as a bandleader, composer and arranger in Germany and Italy:\n\n* Songs, Chorals and Dances (2005, Nabel Records)\n\n* Reflections on Mozart (2006, Nabel Records)<ref>{{cite web |url=www.nabelrecords.de |website=Nabel Records}}</ref>\n\n* Desire for Spring (2007, Splasch Records)\n\n* Homage To Nino Rota (2008, Splasch Records)\n \n* The Berlin Album (2011, Jazzwerkstatt Records): Presents several of W\u00f6lk's compositions from his Berlin suite, as well as new arrangements of tunes by Mendelssohn, Weill, Eisler and Holl\u00e4nder.<ref>http://www.musenblaetter.de/artikel.php?aid=8285</ref>\n \n* Another Kind Of Faith (2017, Nabel Records): features W\u00f6lk's jazz arrangements of Protestant chorals by Luther, Walter, Sch\u00fctz and J. S. Bach.<ref>Nabel label webpage</ref>\n\n* Pictures In Sounds (2019, Nabel Records): W\u00f6lk's latest album (released on CD and LP) with his own ensemble encompasses a collection of his original compositions from the last two decades.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nabelrecords.de/nabel/Nabel-CDs/Ekkehard-Woelk-Trio-Pictures-in-Sounds-CD::211.html?language=en |website=Nabel Records |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Compositions==\nAmong his most notable works as a composer, there are several large-scale suites for chamber music ensemble in the last ten years, combined with powerful segments of instrumental improvisation.\nThe first of these compositions happened to be the epic six - mouvement suite  \" Across The Border'`\" which was written in the summer of 2000 for piano trio ( including some intended echoes of music by COPLAND and other classical North American composers. This piece is an elaborate attempt to catch an imaginary atmosphere and the basic emotional experience of perpetual motion in travelling through a vast, wild and unexplored continent, musically alternating between tightly arranged ensemble parts and vigorously executed jazz - influenced improvisations.\n\nThe collection of compositions under the title \"Pictures in Sounds\" (1999\u20132006) include numbers inspired by non-musical motifs from literature and visual arts, mostly written for piano trio, saxophone and cello.\n\nIn the winter of 2004, Ekkehard W\u00f6lk was invited for a composer`s residency in Ahrenshoop. During that time he worked on the four-part Berlin suite called \"People on Sunday\" (Babylon Revisited) for septet including violin, alto sax, trombone and clarinet besides the regular piano trio in which he musically depicts the course of life on a Sunday in contemporary Berlin from sunrise to sunset.  The suite is structurally inspired by the silent movie by [[Robert Siodmak]] and [[Billy Wilder]], ''[[People on Sunday|Menschen Am Sonntag]]'' (1929).\n\nIn June 2004 W\u00f6lk was invited for another composer`s residency in Toronto, Ontario. While taking part in the Gibraltar Point Artists' Residency, he composed a vast 18-part song cycle called \"Book of images\" based upon early poems by [[Rainer Maria Rilke]] (1875\u20131926) from his publication ''[[The Book of Images]]''.\n\nSome extracts from these suites have been frequently performed by the Ekkehard W\u00f6lk Trio in the past years and have also been recorded live by Deutschlandradio Kultur, Radio Berlin- Brandenburg and Bayerischer Rundfunk M\u00fcnchen.<ref name=\"interview with Ekkehard W\u00f6lk\">interview with Ekkehard W\u00f6lk</ref>\n\n==Festival Appearances==\nHis notable festival appearances include the Mozartfest W\u00fcrzburg where he delivered piano solo renditions of famous opera songs, the International Jazz Festival in New Delhi , Russia (at the Glinka Hall Philharmonic and the Mariinsky Theatre<ref>Mariinsky webpage</ref> in St. Petersburg<ref>The full concert on Youtube</ref>), and also in various European countries including Norway, Estonia, Czech Republic, Belgium and Italy.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101228112749/http://kino.com/video/item.php?product_id=1093 Secrets of a Soul page on Kino]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091005210806/http://www.kino.com/video/item.php?product_id=1175 The Finances of the Grand Duke on Kino]\n* [http://www.omm.de/cds/jazz/ekkehard-woelk-rota.html A review of \"Homage to Nino Rota\" album, in German]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061012033354/http://www.jazzthing.de/review/ekkehard-woelk-trio/songs-chorals-and-dances.shtml A review of \"Songs, Chorals And Dances\" in German]\n* [http://www.kunstfabrik-schlot.de/programm/i_woelk_trio.html Press references in German]{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [http://www.omm.de/cds/jazz/ekkehard-woelk-desire.html A review of \"Desire For Spring\" in German]\n* [http://www.myspace.com/ekkehardwoelktrio Ekkehard W\u00f6lk Trio in MySpace]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wolk, Ekkehard}}\n\n[[Category:German pianists]]\n[[Category:German composers]]\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Schleswig]]\n[[Category:21st-century pianists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2009}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Ekkehard W\u00f6lk\n| image                 = Ekkehard_W\u00f6lk.JPG\n| caption            = Ekkehard W\u00f6lk in 2007.\n| image_size            = 360px\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_date                = {{birth date|df=yes|1967|6|14}}\n| origin              = [[Schleswig]], Germany\n| instrument          = Piano\n| genre               = [[Jazz]], [[Classic]]\n| occupation          = Pianist<br>Composer<br>Arranger\n}}\n\n'''Ekkehard W\u00f6lk''' is a German pianist, arranger, and composer, working in both classical and jazz idioms.\n\n==Early life==\nHe was born in [[Schleswig]], Federal Republic of Germany in 1967. W\u00f6lk started piano training at the age of seven. His classical music teachers and professors were Kevin McKenna (Dublin, Ireland), Hartmut Leistritz (conservatory of Lubeck), Eliza Hansen (conservatory of Hamburg), and Gunther Daubler (conservatory of Wurzburg). His jazz improvisation teachers were Walter Norris, Dieter Glawischnig, Richie Beirach, Philip Catherine, John Taylor, [[Fred Hersch]], and [[Barry Harris]].\n\nAfter graduating from high school in 1987 he studied historical and systematic musicology at the university of Hamburg and later in the mid-1990s at the Humboldt University in Berlin.\n\nFrom 1988 to 1994 he studied classical piano at the conservatories in Hamburg and Lubeck. 1994 he graduated as a concert pianist and music pedagogue.<ref>Online Encyclopedia of Jazz Musicians</ref>\n\nIn 1995 W\u00f6lk moved to Berlin and continued working as a pianist, composer, arranger, bandleader and accompanist\nmostly in classical and jazz musical genres.\n\n==Silent Films==\nA couple of his works for German films have been released on DVD by New York-based company [[Kino International (company)|Kino]]. Secrets of a Soul by [[G. W. Pabst]] from 1926 with Werner Krauss was released in 2008 and The Finances of the Grand Duke by [[F. W. Murnau|Murnau]].\n\nWith the silent movie music trio Blanc Et Noir<ref>{{cite web |url=www.music-for-silent-movies.eu |website=Blanc et Noir |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>, he also performed at the Palais Royal Des Beaux Arts in Brussels, accompanying silent short comedies.\n\nIn the summer of 2019 W\u00f6lk presented his new original quartet composition for the classic German film Madame DuBarry (Ernst Lubitsch, 1919) during the open-air summer festival of UFA Filmn\u00e4chte in Berlin.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ufa-filmnaechte.de/en/ |website=UFA Filmn\u00e4chte}}</ref>\n\n==Recordings==\nHe has seven albums released as a bandleader, composer and arranger in Germany and Italy:\n\n* Songs, Chorals and Dances (2005, Nabel Records)\n\n* Reflections on Mozart (2006, Nabel Records)<ref>{{cite web |url=www.nabelrecords.de |website=Nabel Records}}</ref>\n\n* Desire for Spring (2007, Splasch Records)\n\n* Homage To Nino Rota (2008, Splasch Records)\n \n* The Berlin Album (2011, Jazzwerkstatt Records): Presents several of W\u00f6lk's compositions from his Berlin suite, as well as new arrangements of tunes by Mendelssohn, Weill, Eisler and Holl\u00e4nder.<ref>http://www.musenblaetter.de/artikel.php?aid=8285</ref>\n \n* Another Kind Of Faith (2017, Nabel Records): features W\u00f6lk's jazz arrangements of Protestant chorals by Luther, Walter, Sch\u00fctz and J. S. Bach.<ref>Nabel label webpage</ref>\n\n* Pictures In Sounds (2019, Nabel Records): W\u00f6lk's latest album (released on CD and LP) with his own ensemble encompasses a collection of his original compositions from the last two decades.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nabelrecords.de/nabel/Nabel-CDs/Ekkehard-Woelk-Trio-Pictures-in-Sounds-CD::211.html?language=en |website=Nabel Records |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Compositions==\nAmong his most notable works as a composer, there are several large-scale suites for chamber music ensemble in the last ten years, combined with powerful segments of instrumental improvisation.\nThe first of these compositions happened to be the epic six - mouvement suite  \" Across The Border'`\" which was written in the summer of 2000 for piano trio ( including some intended echoes of music by COPLAND and other classical North American composers. This piece is an elaborate attempt to catch an imaginary atmosphere and the basic emotional experience of perpetual motion in travelling through a vast, wild and unexplored continent, musically alternating between tightly arranged ensemble parts and vigorously executed jazz - influenced improvisations.\n\nThe collection of compositions under the title \"Pictures in Sounds\" (1999\u20132006) include numbers inspired by non-musical motifs from literature and visual arts, mostly written for piano trio, saxophone and cello.\n\nIn the winter of 2004, Ekkehard W\u00f6lk was invited for a composer`s residency in Ahrenshoop. During that time he worked on the four-part Berlin suite called \"People on Sunday\" (Babylon Revisited) for septet including violin, alto sax, trombone and clarinet besides the regular piano trio in which he musically depicts the course of life on a Sunday in contemporary Berlin from sunrise to sunset.  The suite is structurally inspired by the silent movie by [[Robert Siodmak]] and [[Billy Wilder]], ''[[People on Sunday|Menschen Am Sonntag]]'' (1929).\n\nIn June 2004 W\u00f6lk was invited for another composer`s residency in Toronto, Ontario. While taking part in the Gibraltar Point Artists' Residency, he composed a vast 18-part song cycle called \"Book of images\" based upon early poems by [[Rainer Maria Rilke]] (1875\u20131926) from his publication ''[[The Book of Images]]''.\n\nSome extracts from these suites have been frequently performed by the Ekkehard W\u00f6lk Trio in the past years and have also been recorded live by Deutschlandradio Kultur, Radio Berlin- Brandenburg and Bayerischer Rundfunk M\u00fcnchen.<ref name=\"interview with Ekkehard W\u00f6lk\">interview with Ekkehard W\u00f6lk</ref>\n\n==Festival Appearances==\nHis notable festival appearances include the Mozartfest W\u00fcrzburg where he delivered piano solo renditions of famous opera songs, the International Jazz Festival in New Delhi , Russia (at the Glinka Hall Philharmonic and the Mariinsky Theatre<ref>Mariinsky webpage</ref> in St. Petersburg<ref>The full concert on Youtube</ref>), and also in various European countries including Norway, Estonia, Czech Republic, Belgium and Italy.\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101228112749/http://kino.com/video/item.php?product_id=1093 Secrets of a Soul page on Kino]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091005210806/http://www.kino.com/video/item.php?product_id=1175 The Finances of the Grand Duke on Kino]\n* [http://www.omm.de/cds/jazz/ekkehard-woelk-rota.html A review of \"Homage to Nino Rota\" album, in German]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061012033354/http://www.jazzthing.de/review/ekkehard-woelk-trio/songs-chorals-and-dances.shtml A review of \"Songs, Chorals And Dances\" in German]\n* [http://www.kunstfabrik-schlot.de/programm/i_woelk_trio.html Press references in German]{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* [http://www.omm.de/cds/jazz/ekkehard-woelk-desire.html A review of \"Desire For Spring\" in German]\n* [http://www.myspace.com/ekkehardwoelktrio Ekkehard W\u00f6lk Trio in MySpace]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wolk, Ekkehard}}\n\n[[Category:German pianists]]\n[[Category:German composers]]\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Schleswig]]\n[[Category:21st-century pianists]]\n", "name_user": "Greyjoy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSilent Films", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ekkehard_W%C3%B6lk"}
